$$ { #dialect } Notes on Dialect

In general, dialect decisions regarding Kibben have been made for reasons of orthographic clarity rather than with the goal of standardizing a particular pronunciation for the language.
The intent is to simplify the spellings of words as much as possible without introducing additional confusion.
So, for example, WH is maintained (as :| HW |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER }) despite not being a separate phoneme in most English dialects, and R is dropped where it can be inferred, even in dialects which still pronounce it.

Very broadly, spelling decisions are based more on British dialects than they are on American ones, but no attempt at rigidity to any particular variety is made.

$$$ { #dialect.rhoticity } Rhoticity

Kibben is based on non‐rhotic English with some R‐insertion—meaning that an :| R |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER } will never appear in the coda of a syllable, or after short :| Ꜷ |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER }, where its presence is implied: /| aria → :| ꜷ̇ıȷr |: { @en-x-kibben } |/ { .DERIVATION }.
Certain other short vowels change their pronunciation when followed by an :| R |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER }; for more information, see the section on vowels below.

$$$ { #dialect.merge } Merges and nonmerges

Different dialects merge the vowels in /| bath |/ { .SET }, /| palm |/ { .SET }, /| lot |/ { .SET }, /| cloth |/ { .SET }, and /| thought |/ { .SET } differently.
Kibben merges /| bath |/ { .SET } and /| palm |/ { .SET } to short :| Ꜷ |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER } (:| /ɑː/ |: { @en-fonipa }), merges /| lot |/ { .SET } and /| cloth |/ { .SET } to short :| O |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER } (:| /ɒ/ |: { @en-fonipa }), and conveys /| thought |/ { .SET } with short :| O + R |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER } (:| /ɔː/ |: { @en-fonipa }).

$$$ { #dialect.wh } Devoiced W

The WH sound in words like /| where |/ is distinguished from the W sound in words like /| werewolf |/; the former is written :| HW |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER }.

$$$ { #dialect.yod } Yod dropping and coalescence

Yod‐coalescence transforms historic :| /juː/ |: { @en-fonipa } into :| /uː/ |: { @en-fonipa } while affecting the previous consonant.
This typically only affects unstressed syllables, but can cross syllable boundaries.
Kibben observes yod‐coalescence with the following consonants: :| Z |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER } (becomes :| ZC |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER }), :| S |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER } (becomes :| SC |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER }), :| D |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER } (becomes :| GC |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER }), :| T |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER } (becomes :| KC |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER }), and :| Ƒ |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER } (becomes :| ƑC |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER }).
Kibben also observes yod‐coalescence with :| H |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER } (becomes :| HC |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER }) regardless of syllable stress.
When the sequence :| KT |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER } undergoes yod‐coalescence, it is written :| XC |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER }.

In contrast, yod‐dropping transforms historic :| /juː/ |: { @en-fonipa } into :| /uː/ |: { @en-fonipa } *| without |* affecting the previous consonant.
This affects all syllables, but *| cannot |* cross syllable boundaries.
Kibben observes yod‐dropping with the following consonants: stressed :| Z |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER }, stressed :| S |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER }, :| L |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER }, :| R |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER }, and all lenitions except for :| V |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER } and :| F |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER }.

$$ { #consonants } Consonants

There are five series of voiced/devoiced consonants in Kibben: :| G/K |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER }, :| Ƣ/X |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER }, :| Z/S |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER }, :| D/T |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER }, and :| B/P |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER }.
In addition to these are :| H |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER } and :| Ƒ |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER }, which do not have voiced equivalents.
All consonants have both a base form and a lenition; the latter is indicated in most cases by following the letter with a :| C |: { @en-x-kibben } /| cheen → :| kcıȷn |: { @en-x-kibben } |/ { .DERIVATION }, which is represented in Runic as :| ᚳ |: { @en-Runr-x-kibben }.

