$$$ { #vowels.notes } Notes

The dot is a significant diacritic in Kibben.
The letter :| I |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER } should be written dotless when a dot diacritic is not intentional.

The glyph :| Ꜷ |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER } is preferred over :| Å |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER } primarily because of diacritics: :| ‹ å̈̇ › |: { @en-x-kibben } is very cumbersome to read.
:| Ꜷ |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER } is also simpler to write in a cursive script.
However, :| Å |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER } typically has broader font support, and is an acceptable alternate in printed media.

Because :| U |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER } is not used in Kibben words, the digraph :| AU |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER } may also be used in place of the :| Ꜷ |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER } ligature.
In this case, any diacritics should be placed over the :| A |: { @en-x-kibben .UPPER }.

$$ { #sonorants } Sonorants

Sonorants are consonants which can also take the place of vowels in the nucleus of a syllable.
Syllables with vocalic sonorants have no onset but may have additional consonants in their coda.
Unlike vowels and semivowels, sonorants do not have short and long pronunciations.
And unlike consonants, they have no lenition.

There are two varieties of sonorant in Kibben, liquid and nasal:

